Anger is destructive. I probably don't need to write more here, but I will. The face of anger takes many forms. Sometimes it's explosive and unpredictable. Sometimes it's a quiet burn that stonewalls those you love and care about. Sometimes it really feels unmanageable.

It brought you here?? and its not too late

## What's actually going on

It's been said that anger more closely resembles a shield than a sword. Anger, acted out, is usually a defensive response to some kind of pain point or wound. These wounds can be obvious, feeling disrespected, disregarded, or unimportant. Sometimes they are less obvious and reflective of a tightly held worldview that might suggest that they are unlovable, not valuable, or that God is simply "out to get me". And so, as a way of trying to save themselves from pain, they raise the shield. The problem is that you don't need a sword to wound others. You can still bash someone over the head with a shield.

## How counseling helps

challenge the worldviews

learn skills

gain control

## When to reach out

If the people you love have started managing you — watching your moods, going quiet when you walk in — that's the signal. The best time to deal with anger is before it costs you the thing you'd regret most.
